Annotate a map

The package ggthemes has several predefined themes you can customize a ggplot graph, chart, or map.

Required packages

This example uses the following packages:

library(tidyverse)
library(ggthemes)

Sample data

I have a dataframe called countries with national boundaries in Africa. I can use ggplot() and geom_sf() to make a quick chloropleth map with variations in color to represent the estimated GDP.

gdp_map <- ggplot(countries) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = gdp_md_est))

gdp_map

Apply a theme

The map above uses the default theme for ggplot maps. It has a gray background with white gridlines, and a legend on the righthand side of the plot. The ggplot2 package comes with other options for themes, such as theme_bw():

gdp_map +
  theme_bw()

theme_dark():

gdp_map +
  theme_dark()

Or theme_minimal():

gdp_map +
  theme_minimal()

For the most part, these themes were designed with scatterplots in mind. More often than not, for a map, you just want a blank background with no gridlines or axis labels. You can get that with theme_void():

gdp_map +
  theme_void()

The ggthemes package has even more themes to choose from, like theme_economist(), which is meant to make a graph in the style of The Economist magazine.

gdp_map +
  theme_economist()

Or theme_fivethirtyeight, which is meant to make a graph look like the ones published by Nate Silvers FiveThirtyEight website.

gdp_map +
  theme_fivethirtyeight()

Again, most of these were designed for scatter plots and similar graphs. They might be less useful for maps. But one ggthemes theme that is useful for maps is theme_map. It looks a lot like theme_void(), but it places the legend on top of the map, in the bottom left corner, and makes the legend text a little smaller.

gdp_map +
  theme_map()
